In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
In [2]:
# Load the data
data = pd.read_csv("/content/Sales_Data.csv")

Basic Data Cleaning¶

In [3]:
# Removing duplicate rows
data = data.drop_duplicates()
In [4]:
# Fill missing values (you can customize this strategy based on your data)
# For example, filling numerical NaNs with 0 and categorical NaNs with 'Unknown'
data['Customer Age'].fillna(data['Customer Age'].median(), inplace=True)  # Fill missing customer ages with median
data['Gender'].fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)  # Fill missing genders with 'Unknown'
data['State'].fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)  # Fill missing state with 'Unknown'
In [5]:
# Fill numerical columns like Units Purchased, Total Revenue, etc.
data.fillna({'Units Purchased': 0, 'Total Revenue (₹)': 0, 'Total Expense (₹)': 0, 'Net Profit (₹)': 0}, inplace=True)
In [6]:
# Data Cleaning: Convert Date columns to datetime format
data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'], format='%d-%m-%Y', errors='coerce')
data['Delivery Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Delivery Date'], format='%d-%m-%Y', errors='coerce')
In [7]:
# Strip ₹ signs from numeric columns and convert them to numbers
data['Unit Price (₹)'] = data['Unit Price (₹)'].replace({'₹': '', ',': ''}, regex=True).astype(float)
data['Total Revenue (₹)'] = data['Total Revenue (₹)'].replace({'₹': '', ',': ''}, regex=True).astype(float)
data['Total Expense (₹)'] = data['Total Expense (₹)'].replace({'₹': '', ',': ''}, regex=True).astype(float)
data['Net Profit (₹)'] = data['Net Profit (₹)'].replace({'₹': '', ',': ''}, regex=True).astype(float)
In [8]:
# Generate 'Month-Year' column for monthly analysis
data['Month-Year'] = data['Date'].dt.to_period('M').astype(str)

Visualizing Data¶

In [9]:
# Set seaborn style
sns.set(style='whitegrid')

Analysis 1: Month-wise Total Revenue Visualization¶

In [10]:
monthwise_revenue = data.groupby('Month-Year')['Total Revenue (₹)'].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.lineplot(x='Month-Year', y='Total Revenue (₹)', data=monthwise_revenue, marker='o')
plt.title('Month-wise Total Revenue')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Analysis 2: Total Revenue by Product¶

In [11]:
revenue_by_product = data.groupby('Product Name')['Total Revenue (₹)'].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='Product Name', y='Total Revenue (₹)', data=revenue_by_product)
plt.title('Total Revenue by Product')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Analysis 3: Total Units Ordered by Company¶

In [12]:
units_by_company = data.groupby('Company Name')['Units Purchased'].sum().reset_index().sort_values(by='Units Purchased', ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 16))  # Increased figure size further for better spacing
sns.barplot(x='Units Purchased', y='Company Name', data=units_by_company)
plt.title('Total Units Ordered by Company', fontsize=16)

# Adjusting font size and adding slight rotation for better readability
plt.yticks(fontsize=9, rotation=10)  # Font size reduced further and rotation added for readability
plt.xlabel("Units Purchased", fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("Company Name", fontsize=15)

plt.tight_layout()  # Ensure everything fits within the plot area
plt.show()
